United Kingdom","Grimston,Leicestershire,England":"Grimston, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","Sibton, Suffolk, England":"Sibton, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wykham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Wickham  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Wickham","meanings":["English (southeastern): habitational name from any of various places called with Old English <i>wīc</i> ‘specialized farm, dairy farm’ + <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’, such as Wicham (Kent), Wickham (Berkshire, Essex, Hampshire), Wickhambreux (Kent), Wickhambrook (Suffolk), Wyckham (Sussex), Wycomb (Leicestershire), or Wykeham (Lincolnshire, North Yorkshire). Perhaps also from High Wycombe and West Wycombe (both Buckinghamshire), which had forms in <i>-ham</i> from the 16th century. In some instances, however, <i>wīc-hām</i> is associated with a Romano-British town, and <i>wīc</i> is an adaptation of Latin <i>vicus</i>. This is the case for Wickhambrook in Suffolk, the Roman association probably being the Roman villa at nearby Lidgate. Similarly, Wickham Market, also in Suffolk, is associated with a large Roman settlement in nearby Hacheston. The surname is now also common in Ireland (Wexford), where it was taken in the 17th century.","History: Thomas Wickham is recorded as a freeman of Weathersfield, CT, in 1658."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes Wecheham Wykham was born about 1270. She had at least 6 sons with Gervas Hawberk Hauberk. She died about 1401, at the age of 133."},"et":{"about 1270–about 1401?":"umbes 1270–umbes 1401","1270–1343":"1270–1343","1290–1348":"1290–1348","1358–1396":"1358–1396","–1395":"–1395","–1411":"–1411","–1417":"–1417","1270–1401":"1270–1401","1358 (age 40 1398)":"1358","about 1270":"umbes 1270","about 1290":"umbes 1290","1396":"1396","1395":"1395","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1348":"1348","1358":"1358","1401":"1401","1411":"1411","1343":"1343","about 1348":"umbes 1348","after 1396":"pärast 1396","about 1401?":"umbes 1401","after 1343":"pärast 1343","1395 IPM no issue":"1395","1417":"1417","Heredeby, Leicetsershire,England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Heredeby, Leicesterhsire,England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Heredby, Leicestershire,England":"Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Grimston, Leicestershire,England":"Grimston, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Grimston,Leicestershire,England":"Grimston, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sibton, Suffolk, England":"Sibton, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"about 1270–about 1401?":"noin 1270–noin 1401","1270–1343":"1270–1343","1290–1348":"1290–1348","1358–1396":"1358–1396","–1395":"–1395","–1411":"–1411","–1417":"–1417","1270–1401":"1270–1401","1358 (age 40 1398)":"1358","about 1270":"noin 1270","about 1290":"noin 1290","1396":"1396","1395":"1395","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1348":"1348","1358":"1358","1401":"1401","1411":"1411","1343":"1343","about 1348":"noin 1348","after 1396":"1396 jälkeen","about 1401?":"noin 1401","after 1343":"1343 jälkeen","1395 IPM no issue":"1395","1417":"1417","Heredeby, Leicetse